URL reference: https://medium.com/hprog99/mastering-kubernetes-patterns-a-comprehensive-guide-with-examples-45e31564fdb0
DateReviewed: 2025-02-22
Description: Our article today will tackle a popular topic - Kubernetes design patterns. These are small templates that help to solve small pieces of bigger problems, often in a standardized way. We start with a bit of background, and then into the patterns, starting with the Sidecar pattern. The idea here is to add funtionality to your principle container, without adding the code overhead to your principle container. They give an example of centralized logging, where I think the app logs to a log file and the sidecar takes that and sends it to a logging pod. They include a YAML snip as well. Next up is the adapter pattern, and the example they give is an extern service that wants XML, but local code wants to send JSON; so you use the adapter to convert XML<->JSON. YAML snip here too. Last in this section is the Ambassador pattern, and the example they give is an app that needs to do some complex auth to talk to a DB - we let the ambassador proxy the connection for us, and they include a YAML snip. We pivot to what they call structural patterns, and the talk about init containers and stateful service here, with YAML snips. They cover 4 more patterns in 2 more areas - leader election and work queue in behavioral, and operator and sidecar-injection in the advanced area. Good solid intro with decent examples.
BottomLine: Good intro into a number of patterns used in Kubernetes
==
URL reference: https://sysdig.com/blog/kubernetes-limits-requests/
DateReviewed: 2025-02-23
Description: This article will talk about Kubernetes Limits and requests. They start with a bit of background, mainly on how some apps are critical and should always have the needed resources while other apps might be more forgiving. Next up, we get definitions - Limits define the maximum amount of a resource that can be consumed, while requests are the minimum guaranteed amount. They are going to focus on two important resources - CPU and memory. Next is a YAML file with some specs, and then they explain things. They have the most wonderful diagram, where they break down how the various limits and requests interact, and how that shakes out for the node overall. They further detail the effects of exceeding limits and how Kubernetes deals with things -- too much memory, killed with OOM, while too much CPU used means less time scheduled for that pod, throttling it. They talk a bit more in detail, then talk about CPU paticulars - that a CPU is "compressible", meaning that it can be stretched to satisfy all demand. If demand exceeds available CPU, then some pods are run slower than usual, or "throttled". Memory is non-compressible, and if you don't have enough memory, the pod is killed. They go through a few best practices and even touch on setting limits and requests for namespaces. Great article!
BottomLine: Awesome article on Kubernetes limits and requests
